                <h2>Stereotype threat in organizations</h2>
                <p>
                    I also conduct research investigating stereotype threat, or the concern of being evaluated according to a negative stereotype about one’s group, in organizational contexts. Despite the vast array of studies demonstrating the negative consequences of stereotype threat in laboratory settings, very little research has examined the antecedents and consequences of stereotype threat outside the laboratory, particularly in organizational settings. My empirical work in this area has thus far focused on older workers, an important and understudied work group. My colleagues and I found that stereotype threat among older (but not younger) workers is associated with negative work attitudes and greater intentions to quit (von Hippel, Kalokerinos, & Henry, 2013). We followed up this empirical work with a focal article in Industrial and Organizational Psychology: Perspectives on Science and Practice (Kalokerinos, von Hippel, & Zacher, in press), in which we argue that stereotype threat has an important but under-studied impact on organizational outcomes. We’re currently conducting several lines of research in this area, including work investigating stereotype threat among male child protection workers, a project aiming to understand why research seems to have problematic consequences for older, but not younger, workers, and research investigating the how stereotype threat can influence working women’s interest in, and uptake of, work-family policies.
                </p>
